    <item>
      <title>Re: Alternatives to hacking core?</title>
      <link>http://projects.ez.no/enhancedezbinaryfile/forum/general/alternatives_to_hacking_core/re_alternatives_to_hacking_core</link>
      <description>The short answer is that if it's supposed to be part of the collected information process, you will not be able to upload a file without a kernel hack.&#13;
&#13;
The first question is - do you really want or need whatever you are doing to be part of collected information?&#13;
&#13;
It's easy enough to create a form that submits to a custom module that creates a node with any uploaded files as a binary file object and send an email with the attributes of that node including a file (I've done this a few times). &#13;
&#13;
The question is, do you really want users doing that?  If it's a forum and people have to log in to upload files then it's probably fine - but, then, the information collection system isn't really suited for that.  If you just want some way that even anonymous users can upload files (temporarily) that shouldn't be in the database - that's what this extension is for.&#13;
&#13;
The original use for this extension was for people to upload resumes - which is something you probably don't want accessible in the database but do want to be able to route to someone via email.&#13;
&#13;
I'm not sure what the question is "for accessing the results of a submitted file" - depending on your settings, the link to the uploaded file in the var directory should be in the admin template and the mail.  That file will be available over http.  If the link isn't showing, then something else is wrong (is the file there? it won't be without the kernel hack) or check your settings - the display of the link is determined by the settings.&#13;
 </description>
      <author>community@ez.no (Steven E Bailey)</author>
      <guid>http://projects.ez.no/enhancedezbinaryfile/forum/general/alternatives_to_hacking_core/re_alternatives_to_hacking_core</guid>
